1) How can you process large file in java?
Processing a 1 GB file in Java requires a memory-efficient approach.

i) Buffered Streaming (Line by Line):
    BufferedReader reads small chunks into memory
    Only one line at a time is processed
    Memory usage stays very low even for huge files

        String filePath = "largefile.txt";
        try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filePath))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
                // Process each line
                processLine(line);
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        private static void processLine(String line) {
        // Example processing
        System.out.println(line);
        }


ii) Faster Approach: Java NIO (Recommended for Very Large Files)
    Uses lazy loading
    Supports parallel processing
    Uses modern NIO API

        Path path = Path.of("largefile.txt");
        try (Stream<String> lines = Files.lines(path)) {
            lines.forEach(line -> processLine(line));
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        private static void processLine(String line) {
                System.out.println(line);
        }

iii) Very High Performance Method: FileChannel + ByteBuffer: huge files (GBs / TBs).

       RandomAccessFile file = new RandomAccessFile("largefile.txt", "r");
       FileChannel channel = file.getChannel();
       ByteBuffer buffer = ByteBuffer.allocate(1024);
       while (channel.read(buffer) > 0)
       {
            buffer.flip();
            while (buffer.hasRemaining()) {
                 System.out.print((char) buffer.get());
            }
            buffer.clear();
       }
       channel.close();
       file.close();

*** This reads 1 KB chunks at a time.

iv) If Processing Can Be Parallel (Faster): You can use parallel streams. Use only if processing is CPU intensive.
        Files.lines(Path.of("largefile.txt"))
            .parallel()
            .forEach(line -> processLine(line));
